nymic or plural form of   Albino  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Albino","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Ramon, Manuel, Ana, Carlos, Julio, Luis, Raul, Ruben, Alfonso, Andres, Angel.  Italian Pasquale, Angelo, Antonio, Carmine, Giovanni, Luigi, Sal, Santo, Saverio, Ubalda.","Portuguese, Spanish, and southern Italian:","from the personal name <i>Albino</i> (see   Albin  )."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Mowbray","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northern; of Norman origin): habitational name from Montbray (Manche). Robert <i>de Mowbray</i> was Earl of Northumbria 1086–95, but was later imprisoned and deposed for rebelling against William II."],"variants":[{"name":"Mulberry","meanings":["English (Middlesex and Cambridgeshire): variant of   Mowbray  .","Irish (Derry): Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Maoilbhearaigh</b> ‘descendant of the devotee of (Saint) <i>Bearach</i>’."]},{"name":"Moubray","meanings":["English: variant of   Mowbray  ."]},{"name":"Mayberry","meanings":["English: most probably an altered form of   Mowbray  . It is also found as   Maybury  , which has the form of an English habitational name. There is a place near Woking in Surrey so called; however, this is not recorded until 1885 and is 